Synchronous programming is when a function or method expects to be called by another part of the code at a specific time, and it executes immediately or blocks until it is done. Asynchronous programming is when a function or method does not block the main thread of execution, and it can return control to the caller before it is finished. For example, the following function in JavaScript is synchronous:

function sayHello(name) {
  console.log("Hello, " + name);
  // this line never executes because the function blocks
  // for(i = 0; i < arguments.length; i++) {
  //    console.log(arguments[i]);
  // }
}

The following function is asynchronous:

function sayHelloAsync(name) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("Hello, " + name);
      resolve(name);
    }, 2000);
  });
}

